# Accessibility (a11y)

## Core Principles (POUR)
- **Perceivable** - Can users perceive the content?
- **Operable** - Can users operate the interface?
- **Understandable** - Can users understand the content?
- **Robust** - Works across assistive technologies?

## Semantic HTML First
| ❌ Avoid | ✅ Use |
|----------|--------|
| `<div onclick>` | `<button>` |
| `<span>Title</span>` | `<h1>Title</h1>` |
| `<div class="list">` | `<ul>` / `<ol>` |
| `<div class="nav">` | `<nav>` |

## Images
```tsx
// Informative
<img src="chart.png" alt="Sales up 20% in Q4" />

// Decorative
<img src="divider.png" alt="" role="presentation" />
```

## Forms
```tsx
<label htmlFor="email">Email</label>
<input id="email" type="email" aria-required="true" />
<span id="email-error" role="alert">{error}</span>
```

## Keyboard Navigation
- All interactive elements focusable
- Visible focus indicator
- Logical tab order
- No keyboard traps
- Escape closes modals

## ARIA (Use Sparingly)
```tsx
// Only when HTML semantics aren't enough
<div role="alert" aria-live="polite">
  {statusMessage}
</div>
```

## Color & Contrast
- Meet WCAG 2.1 AA: minimum 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text and UI components
- Don't rely on color alone to convey information
- Support reduced motion (prefers-reduced-motion)

## Layout and Targets
- Use landmarks (`<nav>`, `<main>`, `<aside>`, `<header>`, `<footer>`) so screen readers can navigate by region
- Keep focus visible (visible focus indicator on all interactive elements)
- Touch and click targets: minimum 44×44px with spacing between targets so they are easy to tap

## Validation
- Run Lighthouse (a11y audit) and, when possible, W3C validators to catch markup and contrast issues early

## Checklist
- [ ] All images have alt text
- [ ] Forms have labels
- [ ] Keyboard navigable
- [ ] Focus visible and landmarks used
- [ ] Contrast WCAG 2.1 AA; touch targets ≥ 44×44px
- [ ] Headings in order (h1→h2→h3)
- [ ] Links have descriptive text
- [ ] Error messages announced
